{
  "doc_id": "46267",
  "text": "A second issue for clinical application is the duration of effects. In our experiments, the synaptic changes could be rapidly induced, and many eventually reverted in the days after the end of conditioning. The changes could be maintained by continuing the conditioning protocol for several days. It is possible that more prolonged conditioning could lead to more permanent changes. In future studies, longer-lasting changes might also be induced by combining this paradigm with additional methods to strengthen the effects and make them more permanent [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . These include simultaneous DC polarization [CITATION_3] or pharmacological intervention [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Another key factor in obtaining long-term effects is prolonged conditioning during volitional movements [CITATION_6] , which could lead to structural changes and can be implemented with the sort of portable recurrent neural interface described here.",
